# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: california-academy-of-sciences
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The **16th Avenue Tiled Steps**, colloquially known as the **Moraga Steps**, is a stairway in the Golden Gate Heights neighborhood on the West Side of San Francisco, California.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] *Fodor's* calls it "possibly the world's largest mosaic staircase", and it leads up to Grandview Park.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The flight contains 163 steps stretching 90 feet (27 m) high.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] These steps are also covered in over 2,000 unique tiles from over 75,000 glass fragments.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Inspired by the Escadaria Selarón in Brazil, the project was first pitched by two residents of the neighborhood, Jessie Audette and Alice Yee Xavier in 2003.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The duo tried to find a way to link all their neighbors together in an effort to enrich the area.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Aileen Barr and Colette Crutcher, who also designed the nearby Hidden Garden Steps six years later, were chosen by residents to plan the panels of the mosaics.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The project was funded by over 220 sponsored/named tiles which were also placed on the staircase.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Community members all pitched in to create panels together, and three workshops were held.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The Mayor's Neighborhood Beautification Fund also donated to the construction effort.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The opening ceremony was held on August 27, 2005, featuring lion dancers.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Francesco Pignataro, the then-mayor of Caltagirone, Italy, also attended, as the steps' sister, Staircase of Santa Maria del Monte, was located there.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Acting Mayor and member of the Board of Supervisors Sean Elsbernd declared August 27 as 16th Avenue Tiled Steps Day.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Areas nearby the steps rose in crime during 2016, as car robbers took advantage of the tourists viewing the steps to break in.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Both sides of the stairs contain a garden containing native California plants (which support the endangered green hairstreak) and succulents, with the south side being donated by the Xavier family, while the north side was developed in 2006, after a grant was obtained from San Francisco Beautiful.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The San Francisco Succulent Society donated succulents in 2010, and Nature in the City helped with a restoration of the butterfly habitats in 2014.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] One Brick assists in organizing volunteering days, which occur on Earth Day weekend and fall.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The stairs themselves have a design focused on the sky and sea, with sea creatures containing names of sponsors dotted within.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A magnitude 7.9 earthquake struck the coast of Northern California at 05:12 am Pacific Standard Time on Wednesday, April 18, 1906.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] With a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (*Extreme*), it created high-intensity shaking from Eureka on the North Coast to the Salinas Valley, an agricultural region to the south of the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Extensive fires soon broke out in San Francisco and lasted for several days.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] More than 3,000 people died and over 80% of the city was destroyed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The event is remembered as the deadliest earthquake in the history of the United States.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The death toll remains the greatest loss of life from a natural disaster in California's history and high on the list of worst American disasters, natural or man-made.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The San Andreas Fault is a continental transform fault that forms part of the tectonic boundary between the Pacific plate and the North American plate.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The strike-slip fault is characterized by mainly lateral motion in a dextral sense, where the western (Pacific) plate moves northward relative to the eastern (North American) plate.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This fault runs the length of California from the Salton Sea in the south to Cape Mendocino in the north, a distance of about 810 miles (1,300 km).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The maximum observed surface displacement was about 20 feet (6 m); geodetic measurements show displacements of up to 28 feet (8.5 m).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 earthquake preceded the development of the Richter scale.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most widely accepted estimate for the magnitude of the quake on the modern moment magnitude scale is 7.9; values from 7.7 to as high as 8.3 have been proposed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] According to findings published in the *Journal of Geophysical Research*, severe deformations in the Earth's crust took place both before and after the earthquake's impact.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Accumulated strain on the faults in the system was relieved during the earthquake, which is the supposed cause of the damage along the 280-mile-long (450 km) segment of the San Andreas plate boundary.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 rupture propagated both northward and southward for a total of 296 miles (476 km).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Shaking was felt from Oregon to Los Angeles, and as far inland as central Nevada.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A strong foreshock preceded the main shock by about 20 to 25 seconds.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The strong shaking of the main shock lasted about 42 seconds.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] There were decades of minor earthquakes – more than at any other time in the historical record for northern California – before the 1906 quake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] For years, the epicenter of the quake was assumed to be near the town of Olema, in the Point Reyes area of Marin County, due to local earth displacement measurements.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the 1960s, a seismologist at UC Berkeley proposed that the epicenter was more likely offshore of San Francisco, to the northwest of the Golden Gate.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most recent analyses support an offshore location for the epicenter, although significant uncertainty remains.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] An offshore epicenter is supported by the occurrence of a local tsunami recorded by a tide gauge at the San Francisco Presidio; the wave had an amplitude of approximately 3 inches (7.6 cm) and an approximate period of 40–45 minutes.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Analysis of triangulation data before and after the earthquake strongly suggests that the rupture along the San Andreas Fault was about 310 miles (500 km) in length, in agreement with observed intensity data.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The available seismological data support a significantly shorter rupture length, but these observations can be reconciled by allowing propagation at speeds above the S-wave velocity (supershear).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Supershear propagation has now been recognized for many earthquakes associated with strike-slip faulting.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2019, using an old photograph and a recorded eyewitness account, researchers were able to refine the location of the hypocenter of the earthquake as offshore from San Francisco or near San Juan Bautista, confirming previous estimates.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The shaking intensity as described on the Modified Mercalli intensity scale reached XI (*Extreme*) in San Francisco and areas to the north like Santa Rosa where destruction was devastating.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most important characteristic of the shaking intensity noted in Andrew Lawson's 1908 report was the clear correlation of intensity with underlying geologic conditions.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Areas situated in sediment-filled valleys sustained stronger shaking than nearby bedrock sites, and the strongest shaking occurred in areas of former bay where soil liquefaction had occurred.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Modern seismic-zonation practice accounts for the differences in hazard posed by varying geologic conditions.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The main shock was followed by many aftershocks and some remotely triggered events.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As with the 1857 Fort Tejon earthquake, there were fewer aftershocks than would have been expected for a shock of that size.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Very few of them were located along the trace of the 1906 rupture, tending to concentrate near the ends of the rupture or on other structures away from the San Andreas Fault, such as the Hayward Fault.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The only aftershock in the first few days of near MI 5 or greater occurred near Santa Cruz at 14:28 PST on April 18, with a magnitude of about 4.9 M.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The largest aftershock happened at 01:10 PST on April 23, west of Eureka with an estimated magnitude of about 6.7 MI, with another of the same size more than three years later at 22:45 PST on October 28 near Cape Mendocino.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Remotely triggered events included an earthquake swarm in the Imperial Valley area, which culminated in an earthquake of about 6.1 MI at 16:30 PST on April 18, 1906.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Another event of this type occurred at 12:31 PST on April 19, 1906, with an estimated magnitude of about 5.0 MI, and an epicenter beneath Santa Monica Bay.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Seismographs on the U.S. east coast recorded the earthquake some 19 minutes later.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some early death estimates exceeded 500.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Early death counts ranged from 375 to over 500.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] However, hundreds of fatalities in Chinatown went ignored and unrecorded.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The total number of deaths is still uncertain, but various reports presented a range of 700–3,000+.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2005, the city's Board of Supervisors voted unanimously in support of a resolution written by novelist James Dalessandro ("1906") and city historian Gladys Hansen ("Denial of Disaster") to recognize the figure of 3,000+ as the official total.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the deaths occurred within San Francisco, but 189 were reported elsewhere in the Bay Area; nearby cities such as Santa Rosa and San Jose also suffered severe damage.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Between 227,000 and 300,000 people were left homeless out of a population of about 410,000; half of those who evacuated fled across the bay to Oakland and Berkeley.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Newspapers described Golden Gate Park, the Presidio, the Panhandle and the beaches between Ingleside and North Beach as covered with makeshift tents.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] More than two years later, many of these refugee camps were still in operation.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake and fire left long-standing and significant pressures on the development of California.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] At the time of the disaster, San Francisco had been the ninth-largest city in the United States and the largest on the West Coast.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Over a period of 60 years, the city had become the financial, trade, and cultural center of the West, operating the busiest port on the West Coast.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was the "gateway to the Pacific", through which growing U.S. economic and military power was projected into the Pacific and Asia.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Over 80% of the city was destroyed by the earthquake and fire.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Though San Francisco rebuilt quickly, the disaster diverted trade, industry, and population growth south to Los Angeles, which during the 20th century became the largest and most important urban area in the West.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Many of the city's leading poets and writers retreated to Carmel-by-the-Sea where, as "The Barness", they established the arts colony reputation that continues today.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1908 Lawson Report, a study of the 1906 quake led and edited by Professor Andrew Lawson of the University of California, showed that the same San Andreas Fault which had caused the disaster in San Francisco ran close to Los Angeles as well.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was the first natural disaster of its magnitude to be documented by photography and motion picture footage and occurred at a time when the science of seismology was blossoming.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Writing from San Francisco on April 23, five days after the earthquake, resident John W.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Nourse described the scene to his family in Indiana: woken at quarter past five by shaking that made the house "seem like it would break all to pieces," he looked out to see a large brick building completely destroyed in seconds, with fires visible simultaneously to the right, front, and left.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Grabbing the baby's buggy, he and his wife Lena fled to Market Street, which he described as a terrible sight.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Whole blocks reduced to masses of ruins, City Hall a complete wreck.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He left his wife and baby at the mission and returned to try to save their belongings, but found the whole part of the city burning.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] "In traveling over the city it looks like there is not a building but what is more or less damaged," he wrote.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A traveler passing through San Francisco ten days after the earthquake, Mrs.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Baughman of LeMars, Iowa, described a stove placed in front of every house, residents were not permitted to cook indoors, and Market Street sunken several feet in places, with one point four blocks from the Ferry five feet lower than the sidewalk and the cable car rails warped and twisted.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] She observed soldiers with blue coats throughout the begrimed crowds, groups of listless dazed men in the suburbs, and frame buildings near Valencia Street completely shattered within a radius of several blocks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Writing from Boulder Creek, eighty miles south of San Francisco, former journalist Mathias Forestburg described being violently awakened by the shaking, the house rocking like a boat with timbers creaking and everything thrown to the floor.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He spent the morning dismantling a cracked chimney that was balanced on three bricks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One more aftershock would have brought it down and demolished the house.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He reported continual shaking every day and night since the earthquake, keeping the community on constant alert, and noted that all business had stopped and all who could afford to leave were going east.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most immediate firsthand account came from Lewis A.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Spitzer of San Jose, who wrote to his brother-in-law in Virginia at midnight on the day of the earthquake itself.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Spitzer had been staying at a mineral spring in the mountains the previous night; waking just before 5 AM, he was thrown against the wall at 5:15 as the shock struck while he was putting a pan of water on the stove.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Electric cars had stopped running and he hired a farmer to bring him home by buggy.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He found his house standing with only cracked plaster, but described San Jose as "in ruins.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Fine business houses flat on the ground" and San Francisco as nearly all in ruins and in flames.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] His son-in-law had arrived from San Francisco reporting that Spitzer's son and his wife and baby appeared to have escaped safely, but the family could not reach them.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The streets were full of people camping in tents, some without tents, afraid to go indoors.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] "I have seen many heart rending scenes in my life," he wrote, "but never any such a terrible scene as this.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Although the impact of the earthquake on San Francisco was the most famous, the earthquake also inflicted considerable damage on several other cities.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] These include San Jose and Santa Rosa, the entire downtown of which was essentially destroyed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Duffy of Owensboro, Kentucky, who had been staying at the St.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Rose Hotel in Santa Rosa, reported being trapped for five hours in the ruins before rescuers reached him.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He finally made his location known by poking a lath through a hole left by a falling steam pipe.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As damaging as the earthquake and its aftershocks were, the fires that burned out of control afterward were far more destructive.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It has been estimated that at least 80%, and at most over 95%, of the total destruction was the result of the subsequent fires.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Within three days, over 30 fires, that were caused by ruptured gas mains, destroyed approximately 25,000 buildings on 490 city blocks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The fires cost an estimated $350 million at the time (equivalent to $9.1 billion in 2024).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The *Ham and Eggs* fire, in the morning on the 18th, at Hayes and Gough Streets, in Hayes Valley, was started by a woman who lit her stove to prepare breakfast, unaware of the badly damaged chimney, destroying a 30-block area, including a college, the Hall of Records and City Hall.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some of the fires were started when San Francisco Fire Department firefighters, untrained in the use of dynamite, attempted to demolish buildings to create firebreaks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The dynamited buildings often caught fire.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan, who would have been responsible for coordinating firefighting efforts, had died from injuries sustained in the initial quake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In total, the fires burned for four days and nights.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the destruction in the city was attributed to the fires, since widespread practice by insurers was to indemnify San Francisco properties from fire but not from earthquake damage.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Army Signal Corps reported that he "was stopped by a fireman who told me that people in that neighborhood were firing their houses...they were told that they would not get their insurance on buildings damaged by the earthquake unless they were damaged by fire".
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One landmark building lost in the fire was the Palace Hotel, subsequently rebuilt, which had many famous visitors including royalty and celebrated performers.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was constructed in 1875 primarily financed by Bank of California co-founder William Ralston, the "man who built San Francisco." In April 1906, the tenor Enrico Caruso and members of the Metropolitan Opera Company came to San Francisco to give a series of performances at the Grand Opera House.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The night after Caruso's performance in *Carmen*, the tenor was awakened in the early morning in his Palace Hotel suite by a strong jolt.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Clutching an autographed photo of President Theodore Roosevelt, Caruso made an effort to get out of the city, first by boat and then by train, and vowed never to return.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Metropolitan Opera Company lost all of its traveling sets and costumes.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some of the greatest losses from fire were in scientific laboratories.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Alice Eastwood, the curator of botany at the California Academy of Sciences in San Francisco, is credited with saving the entire plant type specimen collection of the Academy before the remainder of the largest botanical collection in the western United States was destroyed in the fire.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The entire laboratory and all the records of Benjamin R.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Jacobs, a biochemist who was researching the nutrition of everyday foods, were destroyed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The original California flag used in the 1846 Bear Flag Revolt at Sonoma, stored in a state building in San Francisco, was also destroyed in the fire.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan, was gravely injured when the earthquake first struck and later died from his injuries.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan and his wife had been sleeping in the engine house adjoining the California Hotel on Bush Street when bricks crashed through the roof.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The interim fire chief sent an urgent request to the Presidio for dynamite.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] General Frederick Funston had already decided that the situation required the use of federal troops.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Telephoning a San Francisco Police Department officer, he sent word to Mayor Eugene Schmitz of his decision to assist and then ordered federal troops from nearby Angel Island to mobilize and enter the city.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Explosives were ferried across the bay from the California Powder Works in what is now Hercules.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] During the first few days, soldiers provided valuable services like patrolling streets to discourage looting and guarding buildings such as the U.S.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] They aided the fire department in dynamiting to demolish buildings in the path of the fires.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Army also became responsible for feeding, sheltering, and clothing the tens of thousands of displaced residents of the city.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Under the command of Funston's superior, Major General Adolphus Greely, Commanding Officer of the Pacific Division, over 4,000 federal troops saw service during the emergency.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Police officers, firefighters, and soldiers would regularly commandeer passing civilians for work details to remove rubble and assist in rescues.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] On July 1, 1906, non-military authorities assumed responsibility for relief efforts, and the Army withdrew from the city.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Accusations of soldiers engaging in looting also surfaced.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Retired Captain Edward Ord of the 22nd Infantry Regiment was appointed a special police officer by Schmitz and liaised with Greely for relief work with the 22nd Infantry and other military units involved in the emergency.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Ord later wrote a long letter to his mother on April 20 regarding Schmitz's "Shoot-to-Kill" order and some "despicable" behavior of certain soldiers of the 22nd Infantry who were looting.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He also made it clear that the majority of soldiers served the community well.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Property losses from the disaster have been estimated to be more than $400 million in 1906 dollars.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This is equivalent to $10.4 billion in 2024 dollars.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] An insurance industry source tallies insured losses at $235 million, the equivalent to $6.13 billion in 2024 dollars.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Political and business leaders strongly downplayed the effects of the earthquake, fearing loss of outside investment in the city which was badly needed to rebuild.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake is not even mentioned in the statement.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Fatality and monetary damage estimates were manipulated.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Almost immediately after the quake (and even during the disaster), planning and reconstruction plans were hatched to quickly rebuild the city.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Rebuilding funds were immediately tied up by the fact that virtually all the major banks had been sites of the conflagration, requiring a lengthy wait of seven to ten days before their fire-proof vaults could cool sufficiently to be safely opened.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Bank of Italy (now Bank of America) had evacuated its funds and was able to provide liquidity in the immediate aftermath.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Its president also immediately chartered and financed the sending of two ships to return with shiploads of lumber from Washington and Oregon mills which provided the initial reconstruction materials and surge.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Branner, who was the first to begin study of the San Andreas fault in 1891 complained that the Federal Government of the United States had not conducted the serious studies that were needed to gather data about earthquakes on the west coast.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He said public discussion was being stifled by fears that acknowledgement of earthquakes would drive away business and investors, and that geologists were told not to gather information about the 1906 earthquake, and certainly to not publish it.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some people went as far as to deny that an earthquake had happened.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Eleven days after the earthquake a rare Sunday baseball game was played in New York City (which would not allow regular Sunday baseball until 1919) between the Highlanders (soon to be the Yankees) and the Philadelphia Athletics to raise money for quake survivors.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William James, the pioneering American psychologist, was teaching at Stanford at the time of the earthquake and traveled into San Francisco to observe first-hand its aftermath.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He was most impressed by the positive attitude of the survivors and the speed with which they improvised services and created order out of chaos.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This formed the basis of the chapter "On some Mental Effects of the Earthquake" in his book *Memories and Studies*.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Wells had just arrived in New York on his first visit to America when he learned of the San Francisco earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] What struck him about the reaction of those around him was that "it does not seem to have affected any one with a sense of final destruction, with any foreboding of irreparable disaster.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Every one is talking of it this afternoon, and no one is in the least degree dismayed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] I have talked and listened in two clubs, watched people in cars and in the street, and one man is glad that Chinatown will be cleared out for good; another's chief solicitude is for Millet's *Man with a Hoe*.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] 'They'll cut it out of the frame,' he says, a little anxiously.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] 'Sure.' But there is no doubt anywhere that San Francisco can be rebuilt, larger, better, and soon.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Just as there would be none at all if all this New York that has so obsessed me with its limitless bigness was itself a blazing ruin.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was crucial in the development of the University of California, San Francisco and its medical facilities.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Until 1906, the school faculty had provided care at the City-County Hospital (now the San Francisco General Hospital), but did not have a hospital of its own.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Following the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, more than 40,000 people were relocated to a makeshift tent city in Golden Gate Park and were treated by the faculty of the Affiliated Colleges.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This brought the school, which until then was located on the western outskirts of the city, in contact with significant population and fueled the commitment of the school towards civic responsibility and health care, increasing the momentum towards the construction of its own health facilities.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In April 1907, one of the buildings was renovated for outpatient care with 75 beds.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This created the need to train nursing students, and the UC Training School for Nurses was established, adding a fourth professional school to the Affiliated Colleges.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The grandeur of citywide reconstruction schemes required investment from Eastern monetary sources, hence the spin and de-emphasis of the earthquake, the promulgation of the tough new building codes, and subsequent reputation sensitive actions such as the official low death toll.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One of the more famous and ambitious plans came from famed urban planner Daniel Burnham.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] But this plan was dismissed during the aftermath of the earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] For example, real estate investors and other land owners were against the idea because of the large amount of land the city would have to purchase to realize such proposals.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Limestone used to reconstruct city buildings was quarried at the nearby Rockaway Quarry.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] City fathers likewise attempted at the time to eliminate the Chinese population and export Chinatown (and other poor populations) to the edge of the county where the Chinese could still contribute to the local taxbase.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Chinese occupants had other ideas and prevailed instead.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Chinatown was rebuilt in the newer, modern, Western form that exists today.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The destruction of City Hall and the Hall of Records enabled thousands of Chinese immigrants to claim residency and citizenship, creating a backdoor to the Chinese Exclusion Act, and bring in their relatives from China.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was also responsible for the development of the Pacific Heights neighborhood.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The immense power of the earthquake had destroyed almost all of the mansions on Nob Hill except for the James C.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Others that had not been destroyed were dynamited by the Army forces aiding the firefighting efforts in attempts to create firebreaks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As one indirect result, the wealthy looked westward where the land was cheap and relatively undeveloped, and where there were better views.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Constructing new mansions without reclaiming and clearing rubble simply sped attaining new homes in the tent city during the reconstruction.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Reconstruction was swift, and largely completed by 1915, in time for the 1915 Panama–Pacific International Exposition which celebrated the reconstruction of the city and its "rise from the ashes".
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Since 1915, the city has officially commemorated the disaster each year by gathering the remaining survivors at Lotta's Fountain, a fountain in the city's financial district that served as a meeting point during the disaster for people to look for loved ones and exchange information.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Army built 5,610 redwood and fir "relief houses" to accommodate 20,000 displaced people.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The houses were designed by John McLaren, and were grouped in 11 camps, packed close to each other and rented to people for two dollars per month until rebuilding was completed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] They were painted navy blue, partly to blend in with the site and partly because the military had large quantities of navy blue paint on hand.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The camps had a peak population of 16,448 people, but by 1907 most people had moved out.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The camps were then re-used as garages, storage spaces or shops.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The cottages cost on average $100 to build.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The $2 monthly rents went towards the full purchase price of $50.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The last official refugee camp was closed on June 30, 1908.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the cottages have been destroyed, but at least 30 survived.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Of the remaining structures, there is a historically restored pair in the Presidio.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Others have been built on as part of private homes, with a high concentration around the Bernal Heights neighborhood.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One of the modest 720 sq ft (67 m2) homes was purchased in 2006 for more than $600,000.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A 2017 study found that the fire had the effect of increasing the share of land used for nonresidential purposes: "Overall, relative to unburned blocks, residential land shares on burned blocks fell while nonresidential land shares rose by 1931.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The study also provides insight into what held the city back from making these changes before 1906: the presence of old residential buildings.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In reconstruction, developers built relatively fewer of these buildings, and the majority of the reduction came through single-family houses.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Aside from merely expanding nonresidential uses in many neighborhoods, the fire created economic opportunities in new areas, resulting in clusters of business activity that emerged only in the wake of the disaster.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] During the first few days after news of the disaster reached the rest of the world, relief efforts reached over $5,000,000, equivalent to $179,170,000 in 2025.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] London raised hundreds of thousands of dollars.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Individual citizens and businesses donated large sums of money for the relief effort: Standard Oil and Andrew Carnegie each gave $100,000; the Parliament of Canada made a special appropriation of $100,000; and even the Bank of Canada in Ottawa gave $25,000.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The United States Congress quickly appropriated 2.5 million dollars for relief supplies which were immediately rushed to the area, including supplies for food kitchens and many thousands of tents that city dwellers would occupy the next several years.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] These relief efforts were not enough to get families on their feet again, and consequently the burden was placed on wealthier members of the city, who were reluctant to assist in the rebuilding of homes they were not responsible for.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] All residents were eligible for daily meals served from a number of communal soup kitchens, and citizens as far away as Idaho and Utah were known to send daily loaves of bread to San Francisco as relief supplies were coordinated by the railroads.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Insurance companies, faced with staggering claims of $250 million, paid out between $235 million and $265 million on policyholders' claims, often for fire damage only, since shake damage from earthquakes was excluded from coverage under most policies.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] At least 137 insurance companies were directly involved and another 17 as reinsurers.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Lloyd's of London reports having paid all claims in full, more than $50 million, thanks to the leadership of Cuthbert Heath.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Insurance companies in Hartford, Connecticut, report paying every claim in full, with the Hartford Fire Insurance Company paying over $11 million and Aetna Insurance Company almost $3 million.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The insurance payments heavily affected the international financial system.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Gold transfers from European insurance companies to policyholders in San Francisco led to a rise in interest rates, subsequently to a lack of available loans and finally to the Knickerbocker Trust Company crisis of October 1907 which led to the Panic of 1907.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] After the 1906 earthquake, global discussion arose concerning a legally flawless exclusion of the earthquake hazard from fire insurance contracts.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was pressed ahead mainly by re-insurers.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Their aim: a uniform solution to insurance payouts resulting from fires caused by earthquakes.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Until 1910, a few countries, especially in Europe, followed the call for an exclusion of the earthquake hazard from all fire insurance contracts.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the U.S., the question was discussed differently.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] But the traumatized public reacted with fierce opposition.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the second half of 1909, the California State Legislature enacted the California Standard Form of Fire Insurance Policy, which did not contain any earthquake clause.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Thus the state decided that insurers would have to pay again if another earthquake was followed by fires.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Other earthquake-endangered countries followed the California example.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 Centennial Alliance was set up as a clearing-house for various centennial events commemorating the earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Award presentations, religious services, a National Geographic TV movie, a projection of fire onto the Coit Tower, memorials, and lectures were part of the commemorations.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The USGS Earthquake Hazards Program issued a series of Internet documents, and the tourism industry promoted the 100th anniversary as well.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Eleven survivors of the 1906 earthquake attended the centennial commemorations in 2006, including Irma Mae Weule (1899–2008), who was the oldest survivor of the quake at the time of her death in August 2008, aged 109.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Vivian Illing (1900–2009) was believed to be the second-oldest survivor at the time of her death, aged 108, leaving Herbert Hamrol (1903–2009) as the last known remaining survivor at the time of his death, aged 106.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Another survivor, Libera Armstrong (1902–2007), attended the 2006 anniversary but died in 2007, aged 105.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Shortly after Hamrol's death, two additional survivors were discovered.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William Del Monte, then 103, and Jeanette Scola Trapani (1902–2009), 106, stated that they stopped attending events commemorating the earthquake when it became too much trouble for them.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Del Monte and another survivor, Rose Cliver (1902–2012), then 106, attended the earthquake reunion celebration on April 18, 2009, the 103rd anniversary of the earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Nancy Stoner Sage (1905–2010) died, aged 105, in Colorado just three days short of the 104th anniversary of the earthquake on April 18, 2010.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Del Monte attended the event at Lotta's Fountain in 2010.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William Del Monte (1906–2016), who died 11 days shy of his 110th birthday, was thought to be the last survivor.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2005 the National Film Registry added *San Francisco Earthquake and Fire, April 18, 1906*, a newsreel documentary made soon after the earthquake, to its list of American films worthy of preservation.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Worden's gelatin silver prints documenting the destruction were later collected by the Museum of Modern Art in New York, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, and the Oakland Museum of California.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] After the destruction, all that remained of the Alban N.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Towne mansion on Nob Hill were six marble columns and a lintel.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] When viewed from a certain angle, the empty porch perfectly framed the ruins of the smoldering City Hall.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The haunting image became an icon of the 1906 earthquake, due largely to photographs by Worden.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 1909, the columns and lintel were relocated to Golden Gate Park, where, known as Portals of the Past, they became an enduring monument to the city's grief and a symbol of its endurance.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Copyright, Pillsbury Pictures, 18 April 1906.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Its wood interior burned, but its steel, concrete and stone frame survived.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] PDT, the **Loma Prieta earthquake** occurred on the Central Coast of California.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The shock was centered in The Forest of Nisene Marks State Park in Santa Cruz County, approximately 10 mi (16 km) northeast of Santa Cruz on a section of the San Andreas Fault System and was named for the nearby Loma Prieta Peak in the Santa Cruz Mountains.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] With an Mw magnitude of 6.9 and a maximum Modified Mercalli intensity of IX (*Violent*), the shock was responsible for 63 deaths and 3,757 injuries.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Loma Prieta segment of the San Andreas Fault System had been relatively inactive since the 1906 San Francisco earthquake (to the degree that it was designated a seismic gap) until two moderate foreshocks occurred in June 1988 and again in August 1989.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Damage was heavy in Santa Cruz County and less so to the south in Monterey County, but effects extended well to the north into the San Francisco Bay Area, both on the San Francisco Peninsula and across the bay in Oakland.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] No surface faulting occurred, though many other ground failures and landslides were present, especially in the Summit area of the Santa Cruz Mountains.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Liquefaction was also a significant issue, especially in the heavily damaged Marina District of San Francisco, but its effects were also seen in the East Bay, and near the shore of Monterey Bay, where a non-destructive tsunami was also observed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The collapse of a section of the double-deck Nimitz Freeway in Oakland was the site of the largest number of casualties for the event, but the collapse of human-made structures and other related accidents contributed to casualties occurring in San Francisco, Los Gatos, and Santa Cruz.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The history of earthquake investigations in California has been largely focused on the San Andreas Fault system because of its strong influence in the state as the boundary between the Pacific plate and the North American plate; it is the most studied fault on Earth.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Andrew Lawson, a geologist from the University of California, Berkeley, had named the fault after the San Andreas Lake (prior to the occurrence of the 1906 San Francisco earthquake) and later led an investigation into that event.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The San Andreas Fault ruptured for a length of 290 mi (470 km) during the 1906 shock, both to the north of San Francisco and to the south in the Santa Cruz Mountains region.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Several long term forecasts for a large shock along the San Andreas Fault in that area had been made public prior to 1989 (the event and its aftershocks occurred within a recognized seismic gap) but the earthquake that transpired was not what had been anticipated.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The 1989 Loma Prieta event originated on an undiscovered oblique-slip reverse fault that is located adjacent to the San Andreas Fault.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Since many forecasts had been presented for the region near Loma Prieta, seismologists were not taken by surprise by the October 1989 event.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Between 1910 and 1989 there were 20 widely varying forecasts that were announced, with some that were highly specific, covering multiple aspects of an event, while others were less complete and vague.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] An updated forecast was presented in 1988, at which time Lindh took the opportunity to assign a new name to the San Juan Bautista segment – the Loma Prieta segment.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The thirty year probability for one or more M7 earthquakes in the study area was given as 50%, but because of a lack of information and low confidence, a 30% probability was assigned to the Southern Santa Cruz Mountains segment.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Two moderate shocks, referred to as the Lake Elsman earthquakes by the USGS, occurred in the Santa Cruz Mountains region in June 1988 and again in August 1989.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Following each event, the State office of Emergency Services issued (for the first time in Bay Area history) short term advisories for a possible large earthquake, which meant there was "a slightly increased likelihood of an M6.5 event on the Santa Cruz Mountains segment of the San Andreas fault".
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The advisories following the two Lake Elsman events were issued in part because of the statements made by WGCEP and because they were two of the three largest shocks to occur along the 1906 earthquake's rupture zone since 1914.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The ML 5.3 June 1988 and the ML 5.4 August 1989 events also occurred on previously unknown oblique reverse faults and were within 3 mi (4.8 km) of the M6.9 Loma Prieta mainshock epicenter, near the intersection of the San Andreas and Sargent faults.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Each event's aftershock sequence and effect on stress drop was closely examined, and their study indicated that the shocks affected the mainshock's rupture process.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Following the August 8, 1989, shock, in anticipation of an upcoming large earthquake, staff at the University of California, Santa Cruz deployed four accelerometers in the area, which were positioned at the UCSC campus, two residences in Santa Cruz, and a home in Los Gatos.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Unlike other nearby (high gain) seismographs that were overwhelmed (driven off scale) by the large magnitude mainshock, the four accelerometers captured a useful record of the main event and more than half an hour of the early aftershock activity.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The June 27, 1988, shock occurred with a maximum intensity of VI (*Strong*).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Its effects included broken windows in Los Gatos, and other light damage in Holy City, where increased flow was observed at a water well.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Farther away from the Santa Cruz Mountains, pieces of concrete fell from a parking structure at the Sunnyvale Town Center, a two-level shopping mall in Santa Clara County.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] More moderate damage resulted from the August 8, 1989, shock (intensity VII, *Very strong*) when chimneys were toppled in Cupertino, Los Gatos, and Redwood Estates.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Other damage included cracked walls and foundations and broken underground pipes.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At the office of the Los Gatos City Manager, a window that was cracked had also been broken in the earlier shock.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Also in Los Gatos, one man died when he fell or jumped through a window and impacted the ground five stories below.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Loma Prieta earthquake was named for Loma Prieta Peak in the Santa Cruz Mountains, which lies just to the east of the mainshock epicenter.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The duration of the heaviest shaking in the Santa Cruz Mountains was about 15 seconds, but strong ground motion recordings revealed that the duration of shaking was not uniform throughout the affected area (because of different types and thicknesses of soil).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At sites with rocky terrain, the duration was shorter and the shaking was much less intense, and at locations with unconsolidated soil (like the Marina District in San Francisco or the Cypress Street Viaduct in Oakland) the intensity of the shaking was more severe and lasted longer.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The strong motion records also allowed for the causative fault to be determined – the rupture was related to the San Andreas Fault System.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] While a Mercalli Intensity of VIII (*Severe*) covered a large swath of territory relatively close to the epicenter (including the cities of Los Gatos, Santa Cruz, and Watsonville) farther to the north, portions of San Francisco were assessed at intensity IX (*Violent*).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At more than 44 miles (70 km) distant, the San Francisco Bay Area recorded peak horizontal accelerations that were as high as 0.26 *g*, and close to the epicenter they peaked at more than 0.6 *g*.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In a general way, the location of aftershocks of the event delineated the extent of the faulting, which (according to seismologist Bruce Bolt) extended about 24 miles (40 km) in length.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Because the rupture took place bilaterally, the duration of strong shaking was about half of what it would have been had it ruptured in one direction only.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The duration of a typical M6.9 shock with a comparable rupture length would have been about twice as long.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Gregory Beroza, a seismologist with Stanford University, made several distinctions regarding the 1906 and 1989 events.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Near Loma Prieta, the 1906 rupture was more shallow, had more strike-slip, and occurred on a fault that was near vertical.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The 1989 event's oblique-slip rupture was at 10 km and below on a fault plane that dipped 70° to the southwest.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Because much of the slip in 1989 occurred at depth and the rupture propagated up dip, Beroza proposed that the overlying San Andreas Fault actually inhibited further rupture and also maintains that the occurrence of an event at the location that was forecast by the WGCEP in 1988 was coincidental.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The contrasting characteristics of the 1906 and 1989 events were examined by seismologists Hiroo Kanamori and Kenji Satake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The significant amount of vertical displacement in 1989 was a key aspect to consider because a long-term sequence of 1989-type events (with an 80–100-year recurrence interval) normally result in regions with high topographic relief, which is not seen in the Santa Cruz Mountains.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Three scenarios were presented that might explain this disparity.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The first is that the geometry of the San Andreas Fault goes through a transition every several thousand years.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Secondly, slip type could vary from event to event.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] And lastly, the 1989 event did not occur on the San Andreas Fault.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] While the effects of a four-year drought limited the potential of landslides, the steep terrain near the epicenter was prone to movement, and up to 4,000 landslides may have occurred during the event.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The majority of landslides occurred to the southwest of the epicenter, especially along road cuts in the Santa Cruz Mountains and in the Summit Road area, but also along the bluffs of the Pacific Coast, and as far north as the Marin Peninsula.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Highway 17 was blocked for several weeks by a large slide and one person was killed by a rockfall along the coast.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Other areas with certain soil conditions were susceptible to site amplification due to the effects of liquefaction, especially near the shore of San Francisco Bay (where its effects were severe in the Marina District) and to the west of the epicenter near rivers and other bodies of water.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Minor lateral spreading was also seen along the shores of San Francisco Bay and to the south near Monterey Bay.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Other ground effects included downslope movement, slumps, and ground cracks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Fifty-seven of the deaths were directly caused by the earthquake; six further fatalities were ruled to have been caused indirectly.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In addition, there were 3,757 injuries as a result of the earthquake, 400 of which were serious.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The highest number of deaths, 42, occurred in Oakland because of the collapse of the Cypress Street Viaduct on the Nimitz Freeway (Interstate 880), where the upper level of a double-deck portion of the freeway collapsed, crushing the cars on the lower level, and causing crashes on the upper level.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] One 50-foot (15 m) section of the San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge also collapsed, leading to a single fatality, Anamafi Moala, a 23-year-old woman.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Three people were killed in the collapse of buildings along the Pacific Garden Mall in Santa Cruz, and five people were killed in the collapse of a brick wall on Bluxome Street in San Francisco.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When the earthquake hit, the third game of the 1989 World Series baseball championship was about to begin.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Because of the unusual circumstance that both of the World Series teams (the San Francisco Giants and Oakland Athletics) were based in the affected area, many people had left work early or were staying late to participate in after work group viewings and parties.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] As a consequence the normally crowded freeways contained unusually light traffic.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] If traffic had been normal for a Tuesday rush hour, injuries and deaths would certainly have been higher.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The initial media reports failed to take into account the game's effect on traffic and initially estimated the death toll at 300, a number that was corrected to 63 in the days after the earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After the earthquake occurred, a group led by Antony C.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Fraser-Smith of Stanford University reported that the event was preceded by disturbances in background magnetic field noise as measured by a sensor placed in Corralitos, about 4.5 miles (7 km) from the epicenter.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] From October 5, they reported that a substantial increase in noise was measured in the frequency range 0.01–10 Hz.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The measurement instrument was a single-axis search-coil magnetometer that was being used for low frequency research.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Precursor increases of noise apparently started a few days before the earthquake, with noise in the range 0.01–0.5 Hz rising to exceptionally high levels about three hours before the earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Fraser-Smith et al. report remains one of the most frequently cited claims of a specific earthquake precursor; more recent studies have cast doubt on the connection, attributing the Corralitos signals to either unrelated magnetic disturbance or, even more simply, to sensor-system malfunction.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The earthquake caused severe damage in some very specific locations in the Bay Area, most notably on unstable soil in San Francisco and Oakland.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Oakland City Hall was evacuated after the earthquake until a US$80 million (equivalent to US$208 million today) seismic retrofit and hazard abatement work was completed in 1995.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Many other communities sustained severe damage throughout the region located in Alameda, San Mateo, Santa Clara, San Benito, Santa Cruz and Monterey counties.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Major property damage in San Francisco's Marina District 60 mi (97 km) from the epicenter resulted from liquefaction of soil used to create waterfront land.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Other effects included sand volcanoes, landslides and ground ruptures.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Some 12,000 homes and 2,600 businesses were damaged.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) turned people who were homeless prior to the earthquake away from homeless shelters and provided shelter for those with homes prior to the earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In Santa Cruz, close to the epicenter, 40 buildings collapsed, killing six people.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At the Santa Cruz Beach Boardwalk, the Plunge Building was significantly damaged.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Liquefaction also caused damage in the Watsonville area.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] For example, sand volcanoes formed in a field near Pajaro as well as in a strawberry field.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Ford's department store in Watsonville experienced significant damage, including a crack down the front of the building.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Many homes were dislodged if they were not bolted to their foundations.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] There were structural failures of twin bridges across Struve Slough near Watsonville.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In Moss Landing, the liquefaction destroyed the causeway that carried the Moss Beach access road across a tidewater basin, damaged the approach and abutment of the bridge linking Moss Landing spit to the mainland and cracked the paved road on Paul's Island.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In the Old Town historical district of the city of Salinas, unreinforced masonry buildings were partially destroyed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Following the quake, an estimated 1.4 million people experienced power losses that were mainly due to damaged electrical substations.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Many San Francisco radio and television stations were temporarily knocked off the air.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KGO-TV, the local ABC station in San Francisco, was off the air for about 15 minutes, while KRON-TV (at the time the region's NBC affiliate) was off the air for about half an hour, and KGO-AM (ABC News Radio) was off the air for about 40 minutes.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] About an hour and 40 minutes after the quake, Fox affiliate KTVU resumed broadcasting, with their news anchors, Dennis Richmond and Elaine Corral reporting from the station's parking lot.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KCBS-AM (CBS News Radio) switched immediately to backup power and managed to stay on air despite a subsequent generator failure.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KCBS later won a Peabody Award for their news coverage, as did KGO-TV.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The malfunctions during the aftermath of the earthquake caused confusion as to whether an earthquake would cause the Emergency Broadcast System to activate.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KNBR began using an emergency generator, hooking up the signal from a command center right after their nearby studio was severely shaken during the quake, when most of the KNBR staff were at Candlestick for the World Series.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Mayor of San Francisco, Art Agnos, later came on the air and provided an update on the earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Power was restored to most of San Francisco by midnight, and all but 12,000 customers had their power restored within two days.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The quake caused an estimated $6 billion (equivalent to $16 billion today) in property damage, becoming one of the most expensive natural disasters in U.S. history at the time.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Private donations poured into aid relief efforts and on October 26, President George H.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Bush signed a $1.1 billion ($2.9 billion today) earthquake relief package for California.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Four people died in San Francisco's Marina District, four buildings were destroyed by fire, and seven buildings collapsed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Another 63 damaged structures were judged too dangerous to live in.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Among the four deaths, one family lost their infant son who choked on dust while trapped for an hour inside their collapsed apartment.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Marina district was built on a landfill made of a mixture of sand, dirt, rubble, waste, and other materials containing a high percentage of groundwater.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Some of the fill was rubble dumped into San Francisco Bay after the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, but most was sand and debris laid down in preparation for the 1915 Panama-Pacific International Exposition, a celebration of San Francisco's ability to rebound after its catastrophe in 1906.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After the Exposition, apartment buildings were erected on the landfill.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In the 1989 earthquake, the water-saturated unconsolidated mud, sand, and rubble suffered liquefaction, and the earthquake's vertical shock waves rippled the ground more severely.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At the intersection of Beach and Divisadero Streets in San Francisco, a natural gas main rupture caused a major structure fire.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The San Francisco Fire Department selected civilians to help run fire hoses from a distance because the nearby hydrant system failed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Since the bay was only two blocks from the burning buildings, water from the bay was pumped by the fireboat *Phoenix*, to engines on the shore, and from there sprayed on the fire.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The apartment structures that collapsed were older buildings that included ground-floor garages, which engineers refer to as a soft story building.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In Santa Cruz, the Pacific Garden Mall was severely damaged, with falling debris killing three people, half of the six earthquake deaths in Santa Cruz and Monterey Counties.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Some 31 buildings were damaged enough to warrant demolition, seven of which had been listed in the Santa Cruz Historic Building Survey.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The four oldest were built in 1894, the five oldest withstood the 1906 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Immediately, a number of civilians began to free victims from the rubble of Ford's Department Store and the Santa Cruz Coffee Roasting Company – both buildings had collapsed inward on customers and employees alike.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Two police officers crawled through voids in the debris, found one victim alive and another dead inside the coffee house.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Santa Cruz beach lifeguards assisted in moving the victims.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Police dogs were brought in to help locate other victims.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The civilians who were helpful initially, were soon viewed by police and fire officials as a hindrance to operations, with frantic coworkers and friends of a coffee house employee thought to be trapped under the rubble continuing their efforts in the dark.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Police arrested those who refused to stop searching.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] This became a political issue in the following days.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The body of a young woman coffee worker was found under a collapsed wall late the next day.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] During the first few days following the quake, electric power to most Santa Cruz County subscribers was out, and some areas had no water.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Limited phone service remained online, providing a crucial link to rescue workers.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Widespread search operations were organized to find possible victims inside the remains of fallen structures.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] As many as six teams of dogs and their handlers were at work identifying the large number of damaged buildings that held no victims.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The quake claimed one life in Watsonville: a driver who collided with panicked horses after they escaped their collapsed corral.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In other Santa Cruz and Monterey county locations such as Boulder Creek and Moss Landing, a number of structures were damaged, with some knocked off of their foundations.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Many residents slept outside their homes out of concern for further damage from aftershocks, of which there were 51 with magnitudes greater than 3.0 in the following 24 hours, and 16 more the second day.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The earthquake damaged several historic buildings in the Old Town district of Salinas, and some were later demolished.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Damage to the Salinas River rail bridge and subsequent repairs led to reduced traffic on the Monterey Branch Line, which contributed to the discontinuance of freight rail services in western Monterey County.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge suffered severe damage, as a 76-by-50-foot (23 m × 15 m) section of the upper deck on the eastern cantilever side fell onto the deck below.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The quake caused the Oakland side of the bridge to shift 7 in (18 cm) to the east, and caused the bolts of one section to shear off, sending the 250-short-ton (230 t; 500,000 lb; 226,800 kg) section of roadbed crashing down like a trapdoor.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Traffic on both decks came to a halt, blocked by the section of the roadbed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Police began unsnarling the traffic jam, telling drivers to turn their cars around and drive back the way they had come.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Eastbound drivers stuck on the lower deck between the collapse and Yerba Buena Island were routed up to the upper deck and westward back to San Francisco.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] A miscommunication made by emergency workers at Yerba Buena Island routed some drivers the wrong way; they were directed to the upper deck where they drove eastward toward the collapse site.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] One of these drivers did not see the open gap in time; the 1980 Mercury Zephyr plunged over the edge and smashed onto the collapsed roadbed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The driver, Anamafi Moala, died, and the passenger, her brother, was seriously injured.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The family sued the state for their role in Moala's death.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Caltrans removed and replaced the collapsed section, and re-opened the bridge on November 18.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] To assist with transportation during Bay Bridge repairs, Bay Area Rapid Transit ran 24-hour service in the Transbay Tube between the date of the earthquake and December 3 that same year.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The worst disaster of the earthquake was the collapse of the double-deck Cypress Street Viaduct of Interstate 880 in West Oakland.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The failure of a 1.25-mile (2.0 km) section of the viaduct, also known as the "Cypress Structure" and the "Cypress Freeway", killed 42 and injured many more.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Built in the late 1950s and opened to traffic in 1957 (as SR 17), the Cypress Street Viaduct, a stretch of Interstate 880, was a double-deck freeway section made of nonductile reinforced concrete that was constructed above and astride Cypress Street in Oakland.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Roughly half of the land the Cypress Viaduct was built on was filled marshland and the other half somewhat more stable alluvium.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Because of new highway structure design guidelines – the requirement of ductile construction elements – instituted following the 1971 San Fernando earthquake, a limited degree of earthquake reinforcement was retrofitted to the Cypress Viaduct in 1977.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The added elements were longitudinal restraints at transverse expansion joints in the box girder spans, but no studies were made of possible failure modes specific to the Cypress Viaduct.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Caltrans has since received widespread backlash for not thoroughly studying the structure.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When the earthquake hit, the shaking was amplified on the former marshland, and soil liquefaction occurred.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When the earthquake struck, the freeway buckled and twisted before the support columns failed and the upper deck fell on the lower deck.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Forty-two people were crushed to death in their cars.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Cars on the upper deck were tossed around violently, some of them flipped sideways, and some were left dangling at the edge of the freeway.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Nearby residents and factory workers came to the rescue, climbing onto the wreckage with ladders and forklifts and pulling trapped people out of their cars from under a four-foot gap in some sections.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] 60 members of Oakland's Public Works Agency left the nearby city yard and joined rescue efforts.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Employees from Pacific Pipe drove heavy lift equipment to the scene and started using it to raise sections of fallen freeway enough to allow further rescue.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Local workers continued their volunteer operation nonstop until October 21, 1989, when they were forced to pause as U.S.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Bush and California Governor George Deukmejian viewed the damage.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] That same day, survivor Buck Helm was freed from the wreckage, having spent 90 hours trapped in his car.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Dubbed "Lucky Buck" by the local radio, Helm lived for another 29 days on life support, but then died of respiratory failure at the age of 58.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Although the freeway reopened in stages between 1997 and 1999, it was not fully rebuilt until 2001 so that it would comply with safety and reinforcement standards.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In the meantime, traffic was detoured through nearby Interstate 980, causing increased congestion.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Street-level Mandela Parkway now occupies the previous roadbed of the Cypress structure.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Immediately after the earthquake, Bay Area airports were closed so officials could conduct a visual inspection and damage assessment procedures.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] San Jose International Airport, Oakland International Airport and San Francisco International Airport all opened the next morning.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Large cracks in Oakland's runway and taxiway reduced the usable length to two-thirds normal, and damage to the dike required quick remediation to avoid flooding the runway with water from the bay.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Oakland Airport repair costs were assessed at $30 million (equivalent to $82 million today).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] San Francisco Municipal Railway (Muni) lost all power to electric transit systems when the quake hit, but otherwise suffered little damage and no injuries to operators or riders.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Cable cars and electric trains and buses were stalled in place – half of Muni's transport capability was lost for 12 hours.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Muni resorted to Diesel-powered buses to continue abbreviated service until electric power was restored later that night, and electric units could be inspected and readied for service on the morning of October 18.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After 78 hours, 96 percent of Muni services were back in operation, including the cable cars.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Amtrak intercity rail service into Oakland from the *California Zephyr* continued, but the *Coast Starlight* was temporarily suspended north of Salinas because of damage to the Southern Pacific Railroad's Coast Line.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The earthquake changed the Bay Area's automobile transportation landscape.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Not only did the quake force seismic retrofitting of all Bay Area bridges, it caused enough damage that some parts of the region's freeway system had to be demolished.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Damage to the region's transportation system was estimated at $1.8 billion (equivalent to $4.7 billion today).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The 1989 World Series featured the Oakland Athletics and the San Francisco Giants in the first cross-town World Series since 1956.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Game 3 of the series was scheduled to begin at San Francisco's Candlestick Park on October 17 at 5:35 PDT, and American television network ABC began its pre-game show at 5:00 PDT.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When the earthquake struck at approximately 5:04 PDT, sportscaster Tim McCarver was narrating taped highlights of Game 2, which had been played two days prior across the Bay Bridge in Oakland.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Television viewers saw the video signal begin to break up, heard McCarver repeat a sentence as the shaking distracted him, and heard McCarver's colleague Al Michaels exclaim, "I'll tell you what, we're having an earth – ." At that moment, the signal from Candlestick Park was lost.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The combined screams of excitement and panic from fans who had no idea of the devastation elsewhere could be heard in the background.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The first television news report of the earthquake, filed by reporter Mark Coogan, came over KABC-TV in Los Angeles at 5:11 p.m.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KGO-TV, the local owned-and-operated ABC station in San Francisco, lost power for almost 15 minutes upon the start of the earthquake, before beginning its coverage with anchor Cheryl Jennings.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] On KGO-TV's feed during the outage, the network's "World Series" telop graphic was replaced with a station identification slide, recycled from the network's 1986-87 "Together" campaign, with "Please Stand By" text on top of the Circle 7 logo.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] With anchorman Ted Koppel in position in Washington, D.C., ABC News began continuous coverage of the quake at 5:32 p.m.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] PDT, with Al Michaels, in the process, becoming a de facto on-site reporter for ABC.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] CBS News also began coverage around that same time with coverage from its San Francisco affiliate KPIX-TV.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] About an hour later, NBC News also began continuous coverage with Tom Brokaw anchoring and featuring local coverage from its then-San Francisco affiliate, KRON-TV.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] A Goodyear Blimp had already been overhead to cover the baseball game, and ABC used it to capture images of damage to the Bay Bridge and other locations.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Local Fox affiliate KTVU was knocked off the air for over 90 minutes before returning to the air with a raw feed fed from one of the station's remote trucks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KTVU anchors Dennis Richmond and Elaine Corral began their coverage from the station's parking lot, as power had not yet been restored to that section of Oakland.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Inside Candlestick Park, fewer than half of the more than 62,000 fans had reached their seats by the time of the quake, and the load on the structure of the stadium was lower than maximum.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] There had also been a seismic-strengthening project previously completed on the upper deck concrete windscreen that may have prevented large numbers of injuries in the event of serious damage or even a catastrophic collapse.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Fans reported that the stadium moved in an articulated manner as the earthquake wave passed through it, that the light standards swayed by many feet, and that the concrete upper deck windscreen moved in a wave-like manner over a distance of several feet.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When electrical power to the stadium was lost, someone drove a police car onto the field, where an officer used the car's public address system to advise that the game had been postponed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After the shaking subsided, many of the players on both teams immediately searched for, and gathered, family and friends from the stands before evacuating the facility.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The October 18, 1989, edition of NBC's *Today* that covered the earthquake ran until noon Eastern Time.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Bryant Gumbel, Jane Pauley and Deborah Norville anchored from Chicago (where they had planned to originally do a special celebratory edition), with reports done by Bob Jamieson and Don Oliver in San Francisco, and George Lewis in Oakland.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Jim Miklaszewski and Bob Hager covered disaster response from Washington.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] NBC Sports commentators Bob Costas and Jimmy Cefalo discussed the effect the temblor would have on the 1989 World Series.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The World Series was delayed while the Bay Area started the recovery process.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] While the teams' stadiums had suffered only minor damage, it took several days for power and transmission links at Candlestick Park to be repaired.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After ten days (the longest delay in World Series history), Game 3 was held in San Francisco on October 27, with the Athletics defeating the Giants 13–7; the Athletics then completed the four-game sweep the following afternoon with a 9–6 victory in Game 4.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] It is likely that the World Series game saved many lives, as Bay Area residents who would have normally been on the freeways were at home ready to watch the game when the earthquake hit.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] It is a rough estimate that thousands of people may have otherwise been on the Cypress Structure during the 5:00 p.m. rush-hour, as the structure was said to have carried 195,000 vehicles a day.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/44-o-shaughnessy] The line was established on September 10, 1980, intended as a way to connect the Hunters Point, Inner Mission, Sunset District, and Richmond District access to Golden Gate Park, Glen Park station, and Forest Hill station.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/44-o-shaughnessy] The northern segment of the new route was a partial replacement of the 10 Monterey, which was simultaneously rerouted.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/44-o-shaughnessy] The northern terminal was shifted to 6th and California on January 27, 1982.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/44-o-shaughnessy] Owl service on the eastern portion of the line began in 2016.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The **49-Mile Scenic Drive** is a historic scenic road tour highlighting much of San Francisco, California.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] It was created in 1938 by the San Francisco Down Town Association to showcase the city's major attractions and natural beauty during the 1939 Golden Gate International Exposition.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Originally beginning at San Francisco City Hall and ending on Treasure Island, the route has been modified several times since.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] By 1999, the route formed a loop proceeding counterclockwise from Civic Center Plaza, and its length was closer to 48.8 miles (78.5 km).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Modern signage for the route, depicting a seagull in profile on a sky blue background, was erected in 1954 and is maintained by the San Francisco Department of Parking and Traffic.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Owing variously to its length, its labyrinthine route, and the difficulty of driving through a bustling city, the drive remained relatively unpopular with tourists and locals alike.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Permanent closures to vehicular traffic on John F.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Kennedy Drive in Golden Gate Park and on Great Highway in the 2020s made the loop discontinuous.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 2019, the *San Francisco Chronicle* proposed a non-driving alternative that it called the **49-Mile Scenic Route**.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The drive begins on Polk Street opposite San Francisco City Hall.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Circling Civic Center Plaza and passing Bill Graham Civic Auditorium, the San Francisco Public Library's main branch, and the Asian Art Museum, the route continues north along Larkin Street through Little Saigon before turning onto Geary Boulevard and proceeding west up Cathedral Hill.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] After entering Japantown, the drive turns north onto Webster Street before immediately returning east along Post Street, where it continues past Japan Center, Lower Nob Hill, and Union Square.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Grant Avenue, the route again turns north and enters Chinatown through its Dragon Gate.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Drivers are soon directed onto California Street and up Nob Hill, passing its landmark hotels.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Turning north at Grace Cathedral, the route then directs drivers east onto Washington Street, passing the San Francisco Cable Car Museum, then south onto Powell Street for one block before descending east along Clay Street, back into Chinatown.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Portsmouth Square, the route proceeds north along Kearny Street for two blocks and turns northwest onto Columbus Avenue, entering North Beach.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] After passing City Lights Bookstore and turning onto Grant Avenue once more, the route travels for six blocks up Telegraph Hill before turning west onto Lombard Street near Coit Tower.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Passing the Joe DiMaggio Playground, the route turns north toward Fisherman's Wharf on Mason Street.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Jefferson Street, the route proceeds alongside the waterfront—passing Aquatic Park and the San Francisco Maritime Museum with several quick turns heading into the Marina District near Fort Mason.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Over the next few miles, the route passes nearly all of San Francisco's Golden Gate National Recreation Area locations.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route detours through the Marina Green parking lot and takes a path of residential streets to the Palace of Fine Arts, the most prominent remaining structure from the 1915 Panama–Pacific International Exposition.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Continuing for a few blocks each on Baker, Bay, Broderick, Chestnut, and Lyon streets, the route enters the Presidio at Lombard Street.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] At 8.6 miles (13.8 km), the route passes the Letterman Digital Arts Center, proceeds onto Presidio Boulevard, and continues onto Lincoln Boulevard.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route detours through the Presidio's Main Post before returning to Lincoln Boulevard near San Francisco National Cemetery.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Passing above Crissy Field and Fort Point, under the U.S.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Highway 101 (US 101) approach to the Golden Gate Bridge, and above Baker Beach, the route exits the Presidio into Sea Cliff.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Continuing along El Camino del Mar into Lincoln Park, the route passes the Legion of Honor and exits the park into the Richmond District.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Turning westward onto Geary Boulevard, drivers proceed several blocks and continue onto Point Lobos Avenue, soon reaching the Sutro Baths and Cliff House.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route then enters Golden Gate Park and winds through it for about 5 miles (8.0 km)—circling Stow Lake; passing the Japanese Tea Garden, San Francisco Botanical Garden, and California Academy of Sciences; turning at the AIDS Memorial Grove; and exiting the park's East Portal at Stanyan Street.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Briefly skirting the Haight-Ashbury and Cole Valley neighborhoods, the route ascends Parnassus Street and passes the University of California, San Francisco's main campus.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Turning south onto 7th Avenue in the Inner Sunset, the route curves around Mount Sutro and the Laguna Honda Reservoir before turning east and climbing Twin Peaks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] From Twin Peaks Boulevard, drivers are directed into the north peak's parking area and offered unobstructed views of the city below.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route then descends into Corona Heights—built to take full advantage of the views at this height.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Winding its way down the hill, the route takes drivers past the Randall Museum before descending east along 14th Street into San Francisco's prominent gay neighborhood, The Castro.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Now 36.6 miles (58.9 km) into the drive, the route turns southward along tree-lined Dolores Street, passing Mission San Francisco de Asís and Mission Dolores Park while splitting the Castro, Mission District, and Noe Valley en route to Cesar Chavez Street.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Cesar Chavez Street, the route continues east through Potrero Hill before abruptly directing drivers onto northbound I-280.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] After about 40 miles (64 km) of surface streets, the route travels along I-280 for the final 1.5 miles (2.4 km) of that freeway, exiting near Mission Bay and Oracle Park.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] It winds along The Embarcadero and underneath the San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge—once the final leg of the route before its Treasure Island terminus.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Market Street, the route crosses in front of the Ferry Building and shortly thereafter turns westward along Washington Street to enter the Financial District.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Proceeding south on the often-congested Battery Street, the route crosses Market Street and enters the SoMA neighborhood on 1st Street.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Turning again at Howard Street, the route passes the SFMOMA, Yerba Buena Gardens, and Moscone Center before making its final turn onto 9th Street, crossing Market once more, and returning to Civic Center Plaza.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route ends where it began, in front of City Hall, after traveling 46.3 miles (74.5 km).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] In the late 1930s, residents of San Francisco and the greater Bay Area celebrated the completion of both the Golden Gate Bridge and San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Roosevelt was given a vehicular tour of the city, including its two bridges, with Senator William Gibbs McAdoo and Mayor Angelo Joseph Rossi before speaking at the Treasure Island fairgrounds, site of the Golden Gate International Exposition of 1939–40.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Later that year, the San Francisco Down Town Association devised a route from behind City Hall to Treasure Island that was originally titled the "50-Mile Scenic Drive", marking the way with blue and gold triangular signs.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The name was changed shortly thereafter—probably with marketing intentions—to reflect San Francisco's approximate area (46.9 square miles (121 km2)) and reference the California Gold Rush of 1849, from which the term "forty-niner" originates.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The Down Town Association produced brochures highlighting the scenic drive for tourists.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] On September 14, 1938, the 49-Mile Scenic Drive was officially opened by Douglas Corrigan, who had achieved fame (and his nickname, "Wrong Way") earlier in 1938 for claiming to fly from New York City to Los Angeles but ending up in Dublin.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Corrigan drove at least part of the route in reverse on that day.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] After the Golden Gate International Exposition was closed in 1940, control of Treasure Island was transferred to the U.S.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Navy, and the drive was rerouted for the first time.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] During World War II, civilian access to the Presidio was closed, the route effectively closing along with it.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 1947, the drive reopened with an expanded southeastern segment, which now continued south past Mission San Francisco de Asís to Excelsior, McLaren Park, and Visitacion Valley before returning via the Bayshore Freeway and Bryant Street to The Embarcadero.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 1954, the Down Town Association held a contest to design a new sign to mark the route, offering the winner a $100 prize.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Local artist Rex May submitted the winning entry, a seagull in profile on a sky blue background with white and orange text.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The signs have proved a popular target for theft and many portions of the route are unsigned.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The San Francisco Department of Parking and Traffic, which manages the signs, attempts to replace them when they are informed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] By 1976, the drive had been rerouted once more.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The initial segment now moved west from Van Ness Avenue through Japantown, showcasing the recently completed Japan Center.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] A more complex loop through Chinatown included a trip up Nob Hill.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] A formalized detour to Fort Point was indicated, and the route now turned in Lincoln Park to reach Cliff House via Geary Boulevard instead of Fort Miley.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] A longer route through Golden Gate Park now included a circle of Stow Lake from the north, and the southeastern loop to Visitacion Valley was truncated and replaced by a turn on Army Street (Cesar Chavez).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Finally, a new segment on Interstate 280 allowed the drive to return to The Embarcadero.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Changes included beginning at Civic Center Plaza rather than on Van Ness Avenue, removing the former detour to Coit Tower, and traveling on Howard Street instead of Market Street at the end of the route.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Kennedy Drive in Golden Gate Park was closed to vehicular traffic.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 2022, the San Francisco Board of Supervisors voted to permanently keep the 1.5-mile stretch of JFK Drive closed to vehicles, making it a permanent car-free route known as the JFK Promenade.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] On March 14, 2025, a two-mile stretch of Great Highway along the Pacific Ocean was closed to traffic permanently.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] With the road closures in 2020 and 2025, and with no alternative routes either planned or proposed by the San Francisco Department of Public Works, the agency unofficially but effectively decommissioned the Scenic Drive.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The 49-Mile Scenic Route is a modern reimagining of San Francisco's historic 49-Mile Scenic Drive, designed to offer a walkable, bikeable, and transit-friendly exploration of the city's diverse neighborhoods and landmarks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Initiated by San Francisco Chronicle reporters Heather Knight and Peter Hartlaub in 2019, this updated route emphasizes accessibility and inclusivity, moving away from the car-centric approach of the original drive.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] It is a scenic tour of San Francisco designed to be accessible to non-drivers.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] It is an alternative to the 49-Mile Scenic Drive.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 2019, Peter Hartlaub and Heather Knight of the *San Francisco Chronicle* wrote a series of articles about a proposed new scenic route.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] They started by doing the existing scenic drive via a variety of non-car modes of transport to figure out what works when not driving.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] After publishing their initial experience, *Chronicle* readers were invited to take a survey about the proposed scenic route.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route measures just over 49 miles, and adds neighborhoods such as Ingleside, The Bayview, and Bernal Heights, as well as multiple parks.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The scenic route also highlights independent bookstores, neighborhood theaters, museums, art galleries, and restaurants.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] While the scenic drive started at City Hall, the scenic route starts at the San Francisco Chronicle building at 5th and Mission.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] Like the drive, the route proceeds counterclockwise around the city.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The section from the Financial District to the entrance of the Presidio is the same on both the scenic route and the scenic drive.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route leaves off some parts of the Richmond District and Sea Cliff.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] The line runs from the Salesforce Transit Center to Cabrillo and La Playa in the Outer Richmond primarily via McAllister and Fulton Streets.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] Local service during the day midweek is a short turn that terminates outbound at Fulton and 6th Avenue.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] Much of the route runs adjacent to Golden Gate Park.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] The **5R Fulton Rapid** runs an identical route, but makes limited stops east of 6th Avenue to speed up end to end travel times.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] The route operates 24 hours with less frequent short turn Owl service overnight as part of the All Nighter network.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] The Line was originally established as the McAllister streetcar in 1906, running on Market Street, McAllister, Central and Masonic and Fulton.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] It acquired the number 5 in 1909, being the fifth of the United Railroads of San Francisco lines to turn off Market Street.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] Tracks were extended to the ocean at La Playa and Balboa Streets in 1911.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] Rail service was replaced by buses on June 5, 1948, and trolleybus operation began on July 3 the following year.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] The line was renamed to the 5 Fulton in 1976.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] Service was extended to Cabrillo and La Playa in 1995.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] The 5L (later 5R) was established in 2013.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] Muni implemented safety and speed enhancements throughout the corridor between the late 2000s and early 2020s, including bulb-outs, 60-foot (18 m) articulated buses, and bus lanes, among others.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] Overnight "Owl" service was extended from Jones Street to 4th Street on June 10, 2023.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/5-fulton] Due to a budget crisis, as part of the Summer 2025 Muni Service Cuts, weekday daytime 5 service was truncated to Civic Center station on June 21, 2025.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] From the Salesforce Transit Center, buses run on Fremont Street to Market Street.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] The route runs on Market until turning off at Haight Street, which the 7 follows for its length.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] At Golden Gate Park, buses turn south on Stanyan then right on Lincoln.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] The inbound and outbound routes split to use 22nd and 23rd Avenues, respectively, until turning on Noriega.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] Buses loop around at the Great Highway and Ortega, terminating at 48th Avenue.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] The **7X Noriega Express** is an express bus that serves the outer segment of the line with express service downtown.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] It diverts from the 7 between Lincoln and Market.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] The inbound terminus is the Ferry Terminal Plaza.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] The 7X was discontinued in 2020 amid the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] The 7 Haight and Ocean line extended to 49th and La Playa via Lincoln and a former Park and Ocean Railroad right of way through Golden Gate Park.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] The line was truncated to 48th and Lincoln in 1947 after a bridge was deemed unsafe.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] Streetcar service ended on July 3, 1948, and the route was thereafter served by trolleybuses.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] By 1952, the 7 terminated at Golden Gate Park, effectively a short turn of the 71 Haight/Noriega and 72 Haight/Sunset which both continued further south and west.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] The 72 was discontinued in 1983, being partially replaced by the 29 Sunset.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/7-haight-noriega] Rapid buses were discontinued in 2017 and replaced with local service.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The **California Academy of Sciences** is a research institute and natural history museum in San Francisco, California, that is among the largest museums of natural history in the world, housing over 46 million specimens.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The academy began in 1853 as a learned society and still carries out a large amount of original research.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The institution is located in Golden Gate Park on the West Side of San Francisco.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Completely rebuilt in 2008, the academy's primary building in Golden Gate Park covers 400,000 square feet (37,000 m2).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In early 2020, before the COVID-19 pandemic, the California Academy of Sciences had around 500 employees and an annual revenue of about $33 million.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The California Academy of Sciences, California's oldest operating museum and research institution for the natural sciences, is governed by a 41-member board of trustees who are nominated and chosen by the California Academy of Sciences Fellows.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Although some aspects of IBSS collections and research are available for viewing by museum patrons at the "Hidden Wonders" exhibit, most of the research happens in laboratories and facilities, "behind the scenes", and not observable by the public.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In fact, unbeknownst to most patrons, research and administrative facilities occupy nearly 50% of the Academy's physical structure.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The main thrust of the exhibits is natural history.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Besides its museum programs, the California Academy of Sciences offers many educational and community outreach programs to members of the public at large.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] There also is a strong emphasis on environmental concerns, with all the various departments collaborating closely to focus on systematic biology and biodiversity.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Academy researchers study life around the world: a 2011 expedition to the Philippines discovered an estimated 300 species new to science.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The Academy publishes the peer-reviewed journal *Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences*, as well as *Occasional Papers*, *Memoirs*, and *Special Publications*.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The *California Academy of Natural Sciences* was founded in 1853, only three years after California joined the United States, becoming the first society of its kind in the Western US.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Its stated aim was to undertake "a thorough systematic survey of every portion of the State and the collection of a cabinet of her rare and rich productions." It was renamed as the more inclusive *California Academy of Sciences* in 1868.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In 1892, Alice Eastwood, a botanist, was hired by the academy and worked there until she retired in 1949.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] She saved the academy's collection of plant type specimens when the academy was destroyed in the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, and built back up the other herbarium specimens that had been lost to over 300,000.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The academy's first official museum opened in 1874 at the corner of California and Dupont Streets (now Grant Avenue) in what is now Chinatown, and drew up to 80,000 visitors a year.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] To accommodate its increasing popularity, the academy moved to a new and larger building on Market Street in 1891, funded by the legacy of James Lick, a 19th-century San Francisco real estate mogul, entrepreneur, and philanthropist.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] However, only fifteen years later, the Market Street facility fell victim to the 1906 San Francisco earthquake and three days of fire, which also wiped out all but a wheelbarrow full of the academy's library and specimen collections.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In the widespread destruction occurring in the aftermath of the quake, academy curators and staffers only were able to retrieve a single cart of materials, including academy minute books, membership records, and 2,000 type specimens.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The 1905–1906 scientific collecting expedition to the Galápagos Islands (the first of several sponsored by the academy to the archipelago) already was underway, and it returned seven months later, providing replacement collections for those lost.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In 1916, the Academy moved to the North American Hall of Birds and Mammals in Golden Gate Park, the first building on the site that was to become its permanent home.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In 1923, the Steinhart Aquarium was added, followed in 1934 by the Simson African Hall.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] During World War II, the Academy contributed to the American war effort by using its workshop facilities to repair optical and navigational equipment for United States Navy ships; San Francisco was a major port for the Pacific War arena.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The post-war years saw a flurry of new construction on the site; the Science Hall was added in 1951, followed by the Morrison Planetarium in 1952.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The Morrison Planetarium was the seventh major planetarium to open in the United States and featured a one-of-a-kind star projector, built by Academy staff members (in part using the expertise gained doing the optical work for the US Navy during World War II).
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The Academy Projector projected irregularly shaped stars, rather than the circular stars projected by many optical star projectors.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The irregular shapes were created by placing variously sized grains of silicon carbide onto the glass star plates by hand, then aluminizing the plates, and brushing away the silicon carbide grains.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In 1959, the Malliard Library, Eastwood Hall of Botany, and Livermore Room all were added.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Throughout the 1960s, universities concentrating on the new field of molecular biology divested themselves of their traditional specimen collections, entrusting them to the academy and leading to a rapid growth of the Academy's holdings.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In 1969, another new building, Cowell Hall, was added to the site.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In 1976, several new galleries were opened, and the following year, in 1977, the "fish roundabout" was constructed.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Before the old building being torn down in 2005, there was a *Life through Time* gallery, housing a large display on evolution and paleontology.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] There was a Gem and Mineral Hall, a section on Earthquakes, and a Gary Larson exhibit.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The academy buildings were damaged significantly in the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Subsequently, the Bird Hall building was closed to ensure public safety.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The inadequately engineered Steinhart Aquarium suffered dramatic seismic damage from the 1989 earthquake, as well.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] As plans were made to repair the damage and make the buildings seismically stable, it was realized that a considerable amount of work would be needed to bring the buildings up to modern standards.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] This led to the idea of giving the academy a complete overhaul, thus motivating the closing of the main site.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Construction began on the new $500 million building on September 12, 2005, while the exhibits were moved to 875 Howard Street for a temporary museum.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The academy reopened with a free day on September 27, 2008.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] For most of the day, the line for admittance was over a mile (nearly two kilometers) long, and although over 15,000 people were admitted, several thousands more had to be turned away.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] In May 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, the Academy announced that it would lay off 105 of its then 504 employees, furlough 96 others, and enact pay cuts among part of the rest.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Due to the COVID-19 lockdown's effect on ticket sales, the organization was expecting its revenue to decrease by around $12 million (36%) in the next fiscal year.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The design architect for the museum replacement project was Renzo Piano.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] His design was awarded the Urban Land Institute (ULI) Award for Excellence for the Americas region in 2008, as well as the Holcim Award Silver for sustainable construction projects in the North America region in 2005.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] One critic praised the building as a "blazingly uncynical embrace of the Enlightenment values of truth and reason", and a "comforting reminder of the civilizing function of great art in a barbaric age".
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The new building emphasizes environmentally friendly design, in keeping with the academy's focus on ecological concerns and environmental sustainability.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] It received Platinum certification under the LEED program.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] This project was featured on the Discovery Channel *Extreme Engineering* series in 2006, the National Geographic Channel *Man-Made* series in July 2008, and Smithsonian Channel's *How Do They Build That?* in August 2022.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The California Academy of Sciences green roof has several environmentally friendly features and a sustainable design.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Renzo Piano was inspired by seven major hills of San Francisco, which typically refers to: Telegraph Hill, Nob Hill, Russian Hill, Rincon Hill, Mount Sutro, Twin Peaks and Mount Davidson.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The living green roof was planted with 1.7 million California native plants.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] The museum's central piazza lies beneath a massive glass ceiling on the roof, which opens to allow cool night air to flow into the building below; by using this kind of natural ventilation instead of air conditioning to regulate interior temperature, the building becomes more energy efficient.
[src:california-academy-of-sciences/california-academy-of-sciences] Renzo Piano and SWA Group won the American Society of Landscape Architects (ASLA) Award in design in 2009.
